div.font: A forward-facing ALB (Application Load Balancer) distributes incoming traffic across multiple targets, improving availability, scalability, and performance of applications hosted in your VPC, and ensuring efficient resource utilization.

div.font: Multiple Availability Zones (AZs) in an AWS architecture enhance fault tolerance and high availability by distributing resources across geographically separated locations, ensuring that applications remain operational even if one AZ experiences an outage.

div.font: A NAT Gateway allows private subnet resources in a VPC to access the internet for software updates, without exposing them directly. It provides outbound internet traffic and scales automatically to meet demand, enhancing security and manageability in AWS architectures.

div.font: Web tier EC2 instances handle HTTP/S traffic, serving as the front-end for your application. They process incoming user requests, host web servers, and interface with backend services, ensuring smooth user experiences and efficient request management within your VPC.

div.font: Auto Scaling groups for the web tier dynamically adjust the number of EC2 instances based on traffic demand. This ensures optimal performance, scales resources up during peak periods, and down during low traffic, maintaining cost-efficiency and availability in your AWS architecture.

div.font: Amazon RDS (Relational Database Service) provides managed databases in your AWS architecture. It supports various database engines, handles routine tasks like backups and scaling, and integrates seamlessly with other AWS services for secure, reliable data storage and retrieval.
